<h1>To Robert Cary &amp; Company</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Gentn</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Mount Vernon July 5th 1761</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>The Fleet is arrivd but some Ships are missing, among which number Captn Jno. Johnston happens to be one, and a report prevails that he is taken, but from whence it arises I really cant
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-07-02-pb-0050">[50]</span>
say. I believe it is conjecture only, but at the sametime I must observe it is a conjecture founded upon very probable Circumstances since the Fleet has been in 14 or 15 days and no accounts of him.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-07-02-0027-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-07-02-0027-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
<p>Receiving my Goods so late in the year as this is, is attended with many disadvantages, but it will proove a real Misfortune to me if they shoud now be lostIn this Event I beg that you will upon the first certain advice of it, have others, exactly agreable to my former Orders, Shipd by the first Vessell bound to this, or Rappahannock RiverI have no doubts of my Goods being Insurdbut this, altho^ it is some recompense in regard to the Expence, is none as to the Disappointment.</p>
<p>By Captn Coverdale (the Ships name I really do not know, however She is in Mr Bacons employ) I send you Eleven Hhds more of my Potomack Tobacco, on which please to ensure no more than Eighty pounds<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-07-02-0027-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-07-02-0027-fn-0002-ptr">2</a>In this you will perceive I follow the same Conduct as I did by the Bland Captn Wyliethat is, to risque a part<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-07-02-0027-fn-0003" id="GEWN-02-07-02-0027-fn-0003-ptr">3</a>I cannot say exactly when this Ship will Sail, but dare believe not till sometime in Augustperhaps the first of that Month.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-07-02-0027-fn-0004" id="GEWN-02-07-02-0027-fn-0004-ptr">4</a></p>
<p>The Sudden Notice I got of this oppertunity, and little time allowd to write in, will not suffer me to descend to particulars, I shall therefore inform you only, that Boyce arrivd sometime ago, and that I directed my Steward on York River to order the Deleviry of the Tobo I promisd you in my Letter of the 3d of April<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-07-02-0027-fn-0005" id="GEWN-02-07-02-0027-fn-0005-ptr">5</a>I dont doubt but they are on board by this time, and as soon as I get advice of it you shall be informd, that Insurance may be made thereon. I am Gentn Yr Most Obedt Hble Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Go: Washington</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-07-02-0027-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Signed: a letter in the handwriting of, and signed by, the author ]">ALS</abbr>, deposited at John Rylands Library, Manchester, Great Britain; 
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Book ]">ALB</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
 The two are nearly identical. According to the <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Book ]">ALB</abbr> copy, GW sent this letter by Gilbert Bain whose ship <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Endeavour</span> cleared the South Potomac naval office on 13 July 1761. The <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Signed: a letter in the handwriting of, and signed by, the author ]">ALS</abbr> is docketed, Recd the 11 Sep. <img class="char" src="images/char-per-trans.png" alt="[per]"/> Via Glasgow Ansr. 16 Sep. <img class="char" src="images/char-per-trans.png" alt="[per]"/> Walker.</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-07-02-0027-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-07-02-0027-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>For the goods shipped on board the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Polly</span>, John Johnstoun captain, see the <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-07-02-0011" class="document">Invoice from Robert Cary &amp; Co., 31 Mar. 1761</a><span class="choice deletion" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover_choice ] header=[]  body=[ Deleted: ', printed above' &lt;span style='font-size: 90%'&gt;[[2014-11-11]]&lt;/span&gt; ]"><img alt="deletion" src="images/deletion_mark-trans.png" style="border:none;vertical-align: text-bottom; padding-right:2px"/></span>. The <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Polly</span> had already cleared the South Potomac naval office, and on 14 July GW reported to Cary that she was safe Anchord in the River. When he wrote Cary on 1 Aug., he had the goods in hand.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-07-02-0027-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-07-02-0027-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>The ship <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Sarah</span>, Norrisson Coverdale captain, cleared the South Potomac naval office on 14 Aug. 1761. In August 1761 GW recorded in his account
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-07-02-pb-0051">[51]</span>
with Robert Cary &amp; Co. (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Manuscript Ledger Book 1, 1750-72, in George Washington Papers, Library of Congress. ]">Ledger A</span>, 67), 108 for the twelve hogsheads shipped in the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Sarah</span>. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-07-02-0062" class="document">GW to Cary, 25 Jan. 1762.</a></p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-07-02-0027-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-07-02-0027-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-07-02-0016&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-07-02-0016-fn-0001#GEWN-02-07-02-0016-fn-0001" class="document">GW to Cary, 3 April 1761, n.1.</a></p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-07-02-0027-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-02-07-02-0027-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-07-02-0027&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-07-02-0027-fn-0002#GEWN-02-07-02-0027-fn-0002" class="document">note 2.</a></p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-07-02-0027-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-02-07-02-0027-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-07-02-0016&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-07-02-0016-fn-0003#GEWN-02-07-02-0016-fn-0003" class="document">GW to Cary, 3 April 1761, n.3.</a></p>

</div>
